[The rapid rise of cases with a predominance of pneumonic plague as well as infection in health care workers are both very worrisome.

Date / Cases / Deaths
---------------------
14 Sep 2017 / 28 / 5
30 Sep 2017 / 73 / 17
3 Oct 2017 / 194 / 30
5 Oct 2017 / 258 / 36
7 Oct 2017 / 343 / 42
8 Oct 2017 / 387 / 45
9 Oct 2017 / 449 / 48

It is frightening to monitor substantial outbreaks of infectious diseases in 2017. Although the specter of emerging zoonoses such as influenza H7N9 is worrisome (the pandemic clock is ticking, we just do not know what time it is), this year some of the old favorites are back on the front page:

- Plague in Madagascar with urban cases and a predominance of pneumonic involvement with large numbers relatively early in plague season on the island and at least one case exported to Seychelles;

- Cholera in horrific numbers in Yemen, already in almost 6 months approaching 6 years of cases in Haiti, occurring in not just drought or flooding but in the midst of overt military conflict;

- Hepatitis A in the USA, in southern California and eastern Michigan, occurring in substantial numbers not related to a contamination food but rather a product of unsanitary living conditions in homeless and illicit drug user population.

With global warming and climate change, continued warfare throughout the world, and the widening societal gaps in both the 1st and 3rd worlds, those of us involved in both public health and Public Health must remain ever vigilant to adapt our roles and change our paradigms to deal with these changes resulting in old and new pathogens. - Mod.LL

